{"id":"2111.01268","submitter":"Jibitesh Dutta","authors":"Wompherdeiki Khyllep, Jibitesh Dutta, Spyros Basilakos and Emmanuel N.\n  Saridakis","title":"Background evolution and growth of structures in interacting dark energy\n  through dynamical system analysis","comments":"13 pages, 5 figures, version to appear in Phys.Rev.D","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. D 105, 043511 (2022)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.105.043511","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc astro-ph.CO hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We apply the formalism of dynamical system analysis to investigate the\nevolution of interacting dark energy scenarios at the background and\nperturbation levels in a unified way. Since the resulting dynamical system\ncontains the extra perturbation variable related to the matter overdensity, the\ncritical points of the background analysis split, corresponding to different\nbehavior of matter perturbations, and hence to stability properties. From the\ncombined analysis, we find critical points that describe the non-accelerating\nmatter-dominated epoch with the correct growth of matter structure, and the\nfact that they are saddle provides the natural exit from this phase.\nFurthermore, we find stable attractors at late times corresponding to a dark\nenergy-dominated accelerated solution with constant matter perturbations, as\nrequired by observations. Thus, interacting cosmology can describe the matter\nand dark energy epochs correctly, both at the background and perturbation\nlevels, which reveals the capabilities of the interaction.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 1 Nov 2021 21:28:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 16 Jan 2022 08:11:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-10"}
